<h1>Introduction</h1><p>The following pages provide the updated pipeline of potential investment opportunities, consisting of: </p><ul><li>Opportunities that we have researched and will continue to actively monitor, and </li><li>New opportunities we find promising and plan to do more research on. </li></ul><p>Updates since February 2016:</p><p>Updated our assessment on several organizations: (<em>organizations in </em><strong>GREEN </strong><em>and pages 2-5</em>)</p><p>Identified new ideas to research: ASAP, Charter School Growth Fund, Nurture Science Center, Early College High School, Health Leads, LIFT, ReachUp USA<strong>  </strong><em>(organizations in </em><strong>BLUE</strong>)</p><p>Sharpened our perspective on Attendance, Alternatives to Incarceration, Access to Public Benefits, and Cash Transfers – including looking at organizations working in these domains (<em>see pages 6-7</em>)</p><p>While organized by the most relevant categories, this list is not meant to convey any prioritization of specific areas. alt="image" /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Teacher turnover and effectiveness significantly impact student outcomes. </p><p>New Teacher Center matches new teachers with carefully selected veteran “teacher mentors” who provide ongoing professional development and coaching to new teachers for 2-3 years, and its model has shown to improve teacher retention and instructional effectiveness.  NTC has worked primarily within the K-12 domain in the past but has recently expanded its early learning (“EL”) work to provide similar services to early childhood educators. </p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>K-12: Evidence of teacher-level outcomes is strong but evidence of student-level outcomes is still in development. Currently undergoing a strategic refresh so the vision for growth is unclear; leadership team is continuing to develop as new hires have joined. Current source of revenue is partnerships with districts.</p><p>EL: NTC is still at an early stage here; evidence is limited and it is not yet clear how NTC will prioritize this work after the strategic refresh. NTC has implemented EL work in school districts that have pre-K; given the fragmented nature of early childhood education, this path may present a challenge to scale nationally. Financial sustainability of this work will need to be further examined.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Continues to be a promising organization but now is not the right time for due diligence as NTC is currently revisiting its strategy and vision. We will follow up on the K-12 work in the coming months to get an update on the strategic refresh, the status of the leadership team, and the vision to scale. For EL, we will learn how it will be prioritized, monitor the evidence, and assess the feasibility of reaching scale and the economic sustainability of the model.</p><h3>Attendance</h3><p>Each year, an estimated 5 to 7.5 million U.S. students in K-12 miss nearly a month of school.</p><p>(more)</p><p>This is particularly alarming because chronic absenteeism, often defined as missing ten percent of the school year or 15 days of school in a year, correlates highly with poor academic performance and low college attainment, and is a strong predictor of dropping out of high school. Yet not until this year has chronic absenteeism been a required metric for schools to report on, and many schools do not know how to intervene effectively to prevent students from being chronically absent.  </p><p>While we do not see any immediate investment opportunities in this space, there is a potential future opportunity to support training and technical assistance that equip schools with the tools to reduce chronic absenteeism.  A path to scale for this work would likely involve focusing on the largest urban school districts (roughly ten percent of all students eligible for free or reduced-price lunch attend the nation’s ten largest school districts, and chronic absenteeism is concentrated among schools with high percentages of low-income students) and working with clusters of districts within states eager to address this issue.  Identifying the right districts should become easier this summer when, for the first time, chronic absence data will be released for schools across the country.</p><p>The two leading organizations working in this space, <strong>Attendance Works </strong>and <strong>Everyone Graduates Center</strong>, have great strengths, including leaders who have a vision for tackling chronic absenteeism nationally and traction with large school districts and state officials.  However, we believe the evidence supporting the interventions of these organization is not yet robust enough.  Attendance Works does not have any external evaluations available.  Everyone Graduates Center does have an evaluation showing that rates of chronic absenteeism were reduced in the schools that implemented its intervention, but its experimental design does not allow us to draw definitive conclusions about causality.  We plan to monitor these organizations in the coming months, paying particular attention to any new reports concerning the evidence for Everyone Graduates Center’s intervention.  We will also keep an eye on other emerging organizations and interventions in this field.</p><h4>Attendance Works</h4><h5>Issue Area</h5><p>Attendance/Chronic Absenteeism</p><h5>Logo</h5><p><img /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Chronic absenteeism correlates with poor student performance and is a predictor of dropping out of high school. </p><p>Attendance Works offers school districts technical assistance, research and tools to reduce chronic absenteeism, and advocates for effective policies at the state and national level.  When schools effectively address this issue, chronic absenteeism rates drop, which ultimately leads to improved student outcomes.  </p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>Attendance Works has some promising preliminary outcomes, but evidence is limited and the organization does not appear to track outcomes consistently. The ED is widely respected, and there could be a pathway to scale through school districts and states. Funding is expected to be allocated to schools with high chronic absenteeism through the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA), the new federal education law.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Impressive reputation in the field and potentially compelling, scalable approach to improving educational outcomes. We would like to see stronger evidence (e.g., a third-party experimental evaluation), more accountability for outcomes, and more clarity on how AW will scale under ESSA; we will closely watch developments on all these points.</p><h4>Everyone Graduates Center</h4><h5>Issue Area</h5><p>Attendance/Chronic Absenteeism</p><h5>Logo</h5><p><img /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Chronic absenteeism correlates with poor student performance and is a predictor of dropping out of high school.</p><p>Everyone Graduates Center, a research program at Johns Hopkins University, provides technical assistance to districts to improve attendance and also develops and disseminates information to promote high school graduation. When schools effectively address this issue, chronic absenteeism rates drop, which ultimately leads to improved student outcomes.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>Intervention model produced promising results but does not yet meet BMP standards of evidence. The director has a strong reputation as a researcher, but the team may need additional operational support to scale effectively. It is securing funding and pursuing scale as the lead attendance-related technical assistance provider for the My Brother’s Keeper initiative in 30 school districts.  Additional funding is expected to be allocated to schools with high chronic absenteeism through ESSA, the new federal education law.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Potentially scalable intervention to improve educational outcomes;<strong><em> </em></strong>the vision to scale the initiative through My Brother’s Keeper is exciting. However, evidence and leadership team capabilities do not yet meet standards for due diligence.  We will watch progress closely and re-assess once the initiative is fully implemented across sites.</p><h3>Charter Schools/CMOs</h3><p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetuer adipiscing elit. /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Roughly 400,000 children are in foster care. These children are vulnerable, likely to have experienced trauma, and are at risk for negative outcomes in the future. </p><p>KEEP, a model of foster parent training, has been shown to reduce behavioral problems, decrease disruptions in foster-care placements, and increase successful exits from foster care, especially for the highest-risk children who have experienced numerous failed placements. These short-term outcomes ultimately improve long-term life trajectories.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>Evidence for KEEP’s model is robust; two randomized controlled trials show improved parenting, lower rates of problem behavior, and fewer placement disruptions. These findings translate into cost savings for foster care agencies.  KEEP has been replicated in five states and is currently being expanded to full potential in Tennessee.  KEEP’s leader, Dr. Patricia Chamberlain, is a well-respected researcher and leading figure in the science of implementing evidence-based practices; however, she does not have experience with taking organizations to scale. </p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Very strong overall. The evidence base for outcomes and the economic case and potential for scaling through states are exciting. Readiness for due diligence hinges on development of the leadership team and organizational capacity, and success in TN; we will monitor these critical points closely.</p><h3>In-Home Support</h3><p>Lorem ipsum sociis natoque penatibus et magnis dis parturient montes, nascetur ridiculus mus. /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Many low-income youth lack access to career pathways, and traditional education and training programs are not keeping up with corporate demand. </p><p>Year Up trains low-income youth with a GED for mid-skill jobs through internship experiences and connects employers with a well-trained, diverse talent pipeline. Year Up’s graduates have a higher likelihood of being enrolled in school and/or being employed, and they earn a higher salary compared to their peers.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>Year Up’s founder and CEO, Gerald Chertavian, is one of the most respected leaders in the nonprofit sector.  He has a vision to close the opportunity divide for low- income youth – i.e., to create job opportunities and readiness at scale – through a combination of direct work with companies and youth, technical assistance to community colleges, and campaigns to drive demand at the corporate level.  Year Up’s evidence and economics for its direct work are robust; the Economic Mobility Corporation called the findings “the most exciting evaluation results in youth employment in 20 or 30 years – and the first to show a really substantial earnings gain.”  Its technical assistance work is still under development.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Highly compelling model – move to due diligence.  Organization is at an inflection point with a very strong leader and leadership team, solid outcomes, unique approach to addressing both demand for youth in jobs and readiness of youth to take those jobs, and vision for scale.  Due diligence to focus on plan for reaching transformative scale through work on driving corporate demand, providing training and technical assistance to community colleges, and other initiatives.</p><h2>Criminal Justice</h2><p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetuer adipiscing elit. Sed consequat, leo eget bibendum sodales, augue velit cursus nunc,</p><h3>Alternatives to Incarceration</h3><p>Millions of low-income people – many of them innocent – are jailed each year because they cannot afford bail to be released before trial.</p><p>(more)</p><p>Research shows that spending as few as two days in jail can lead to negative outcomes; it impacts employment, is associated with future criminal behavior, and could worsen health conditions. Incarceration also harms the more than 3 million children with parents in prison, damaging their education, health and social relationships, and increasing the risk that one day they will go to prison, too. The 500,000 juveniles who are detained annually are 30 percent less likely than other youth to complete high school, and 22 percent more likely to be incarcerated as adults.   Our research has focused on programs that provide funding to low-income individuals so they can pay bail and avoid the negative consequences of spending time in jail when they are not convicted of a crime.  However, we do not believe there is an opportunity for a Blue Meridian investment.  The leading bail fund, <strong>Bronx Freedom Fund</strong>, currently has insufficient evidence and limited capacity.  More important, there is not an apparent pathway to scale. Bail regulations vary significantly across the 3,000 jurisdictions in the U.S., making it unclear how a bail fund might sustainably scale.</p><p>We also revisited alternative-to-incarceration programs, including <strong>AMIkids</strong>, and researched new programs such as <strong>CASES (the Center for Alternate Sentencing and Employment)</strong>. These programs help people avoid the negative consequences of incarceration (detention, in the case of youth) by providing an alternative pathway for individuals who are either awaiting trial or convicted of nonviolent crimes.  However, none of the organizations we assessed had the right combination of size, potential platform for scaling, and evidence base that we seek in candidates for Blue Meridian investment.  Further, due to the highly fragmented and decentralized nature of the criminal and juvenile justice systems, it will likely be difficult to find investment opportunities in the alternative-to-incarceration space and the criminal and juvenile justice fields more broadly.  However, we plan to stay open to learning about new opportunities and to monitor other organizations in the pipeline, including both organizations mentioned above and others, such as CEO, which provide employment services to ex-offenders.</p><h4>The Bronx Freedom Fund</h4><h5>Issue Area</h5><p>Alternatives to Incarceration</p><h5>Logo</h5><p><img /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Research shows that as few as two days in jail can lead to negative outcomes. Yet every year, millions of low-income people who have not been convicted of a crime spend time in jail because they cannot afford bail. </p><p>Bronx Freedom Fund covers the cost of bail for individuals charged with misdemeanors and provides informal technical assistance to organizations to set up bail funds so that less people are detailed in jail prior to trial.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>The relationship between even a short time in jail and poor outcomes is well established, but evidence of the effectiveness of bail funds is currently limited. BFF is very small – serving ~2-3% of the target population in the Bronx – and has limited capacity to scale its fund.  Furthermore, there is no apparent pathway to scale nationally. The bail fund itself is self-renewing, since bail is returned after a defendant makes required court appearances, but continuous funding is required to support the fund operations.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>The bail fund concept is intriguing because of its simplicity and self-renewing economic model. However, we do not see this as an investment opportunity at this time because of BFF’s small size and limited capacity to scale, plus the difficulty of scaling in this arena and lack of peer organizations.</p><h3>Post-Incarceration Supports</h3><p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetuer adipiscing elit. Sed consequat, leo eget bibendum sodales, augue velit cursus nunc,</p><h3>Access to Benefits</h3><p>Public benefits programs for low-income families are one of the most important and effective tools for fighting poverty. Each year these programs lift 48 million people out of poverty, including 12 million children. Despite this, almost 30 million people do not take advantage of the benefits for which they are eligible, leaving ~$95 billion in benefits unclaimed.</p><p>(more)</p><p>Two strategies that address this participation gap are: 1) direct service organizations that help low-income individuals navigate public benefits programs, and 2) technical assistance to state agencies to remove barriers to accessing benefits.</p><p>We do not believe there is an investment opportunity for Blue Meridian in this space at this time. However, we will continue to track two promising organizations: <strong>Single Stop USA</strong> (direct service) and the <strong>Center for Law and Social Policy</strong> (technical assistance). Single Stop is currently undergoing a major leadership transition and the evidence base is not yet strong enough to justify investment. We expect results from a new evaluation of Single Stop, focused on community colleges, to be published in late 2016. At that time we will reevaluate the organization’s evidence and leadership.  The Center for Law and Social Policy lacks sufficient evidence at this time and some questions remain about the replicability of its program model and capacity for growth.  A report on results and outcomes is scheduled to be published in June. If this convincingly demonstrates program effectiveness, we will revisit our assessment.  Finally, we are in the early stages of investigating <strong>Share Our Strength’s No Kid Hungry campaign</strong>, which aims to increase access to school breakfast through technical assistance to school districts, but it is premature to assess the investment potential at this point.</p><h4>Benefits Data Trust</h4><h5>Issue Area</h5><p>Access to Benefits</p><h5>Logo</h5><p><img /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Many low-income people who are eligible for public benefits programs do not receive them. </p><p>Benefits Data Trust connects people to benefits programs through targeted outreach and support throughout the application process.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>BDT has grown significantly in the last three years but there is limited evidence to support its interventions and it does not have a clear platform for scale; also, BDT focuses primarily on senior citizens.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Benefits Data Trust has a compelling track record of recent growth connecting people to public benefits programs, but its evidence is limited and its beneficiaries are mostly senior citizens. We will continue to stay open to revisiting Benefits Data Trust but will not actively monitor it.</p><h4>Single Stop USA</h4><h5>Issue Area</h5><p>Access to Benefits</p><h5>Logo</h5><p><img /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Many low-income people who are eligible for public benefits do not receive them. </p><p>Single Stop connects people to benefits and provides a range of services to support financial stability through one-stop-shop locations.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>Single Stop has a track record of growth and a potential channel to scale through community colleges; however, evidence is limited and it is currently undergoing a leadership transition.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>Single Stop is intriguing because of its potential to scale and develop a sustainable economic model in the community college channel. However, it is currently undergoing a leadership transition and the program’s evidence is insufficient at this time.  We will re-assess in late 2016 based on forthcoming evaluation results, and look at the strength and stability of the leadership team.</p><h4>Center for Law and Social Policy</h4><h5>Issue fRQj93/BPEr28/b9sfDcXiA6RqV5qM2sBZPDtrNokQjshsKkzvvEUjAt5h2zjIIRUG16h+KXhf8AbVtvj9N4v8AeIdfHhm0SG4t7BtV0uOzmY2riS22SfMV8zb87ruDHKtitPx18cp97st8y8cbWryHxh8adR1BnhS/mk/7aE1wVsVTp6Xb+ZrGpJyvyr7tPzJbf9of9snwz4z1/UPGZuireHLyLw/pl5qmkzWcd554aE3DWirIzbMjcijgfMAevLfs6eOv+CiHjTxHceJbTw8rXlu9v/ounNprWfmNKvnLcNPKJDB5ZcqYSsu9VyMZBm8JeEviD8XtcXSPDOmXF07viSRVOyIerHoK+1fgR8HtN+DfgyHQLdlkupPnvLgfxv6fQVnho18VVUm2kn3LnjKdOm0oRu/L/AIJ4h4H8J/t4Q6n8UNM8aXWqtZ6zpVxL4N1RNYsmkhvDbMqQxqJAtqok27SEOT8zsDzTvgFpX7d2g6vovhDx0muf2PY6gYdV1LV7/TbgvYxqRE0cvmy3M0shG6VpcHJ+QKMqPqYjjO2gbR1Fet7Hzf3nH9advhX3Hzn8VLn9uWD4k38Xwu0udtFjvEfT2X+zZLa4s/KLyhhPKs63RmxGnzLAIiS3z4NYt6//AAUe8Q+AtIuNd8BaLaeIrLxBdSSSaH4oCK1ulheLbyNCdscivO1tujklkAYg7CF3r9Tc4zRvPRRVex68z+8PrWiXIvuPl+wvf29NMluNG8Q6f4ovo47TyrXVNHh8OB3BmYNM3myqpuFj2FFEaQ4DFlZsA4a6h/wVKkv7PxF/ZW2FdPtmutDaHRljecWdsZV4nZwWuHulIE+0eUm1gvL/AF9kHjbQRgZJ/wDHaz9j/ef3lfWl/JH7j5f8Y+Of2xNG+Fnw/tTpHiaLxNrHjaa01uLTbTRpr37EllfTR7mcm0jRpYYAz/I2xsfI7ADDuda/4KitotxdyeFIYdQ2XksdrYzaTJGNQXBso90pQ/2S4BFwMm+UlfKkAY7PrhlU8laAndVq3Rej5mEcXGOns4v5f8E+P7XXf+Cg/i7V/wDhItM0HxFDpK6hdQrm40ezuooJGEW+3QvLDMIygkT7TCzhWl4diijlP+Fo/wDBbf8A6JBoH/hCaV/82VfdoCdRGKduHp+lR9Xl/O/vL+ux/wCfcfu/4I6iiiuo4Ao98UUUAFFFFAAaoar4f0TXI/J1bSba4X+7PCG/nV+g57VMtgPPdd/Zk+DHiF2e+8GhS33vIupYwfwDAVT0z9kf4B6XN58fgCGZgcj7VcSyL+RbFemnGPmoXb/DWP1ei3dxRXNIoeH/AA3oPhezXT9A0e2soV6R2sARf0rQooraPKtESFFFFUAUUUUAFFFFABRRRQAUUUUAf//Z" alt="https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/736x/7e/e3/de/7ee3de4b80f8e874d8aaae4bb69d7647.jpg" /></p><h5>Description</h5><p>Many low-income people who are eligible for public benefits do not receive them. </p><p>Work Support Strategies is an initiative - led by the Center for Law and Social Policy (CLASP) and supported by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities and the Urban Institute - that provides TA to state benefits agencies to remove barriers to access.</p><h5>Summary Assessment</h5><p>CLASP lacks sufficient evidence at this time.  Though it has strong leadership, it is unclear whether it has the capacity and there is sufficient state demand to support significant scale.  Because CLASP targets funded entitlement programs, sustainable funding is not required after the initial investment in TA.</p><h5>Current View</h5><p>CLASP is exciting because it targets funded entitlement programs, so sustainable funding is not required after the initial investment in TA. However, evidence of effectiveness is not sufficient at this time.  We will re-assess CLASP in summer 2016 based on forthcoming evaluation results, and look at the replicability of its program model and capacity for growth.</p><h3>Cash Transfers</h3><p>A substantial body of evidence has demonstrated that cash transfers, when structured correctly, can be effective at both addressing short-term poverty and incentivizing long-term investments by low-income households in human capital (e.g., health and education).</p><p>(more)</p><p>These programs frequently target outcomes that benefit children, such as vaccinations, school enrollment, and improved nutrition. However, cash transfer have been implemented and studied primarily in the developing world, and their use in the United States is less common. <strong>Family Rewards</strong> is the largest transfer program that has been attempted in the U.S., with 4,800 families, including 11,000 children, participating in the initial pilot in New York City. Results from this program were mixed, with improvements in some target outcomes and no effect on others. A revised version of the program was launched as Family Rewards 2.0, and evaluation results are forthcoming in late 2016. Both Family Rewards programs were funded primarily by philanthropic capital and it is unclear whether there is a sustainable economic model.</p><p>We do not see any immediate investment opportunities here for Blue Meridian. Despite very promising results from the developing world, evidence to support the effectiveness of cash transfer programs in the U.S. context is not yet conclusive. In addition, cash transfer programs face an unclear path to financial sustainability and no organizations are approaching sufficient scale to merit consideration at this time.  We believe the most promising area to watch for future investment opportunities is programs that provide one-time cash transfers at life moments that are critical for long-term outcomes (e.g., at the birth of a child or to complete college), and we will continue to monitor developments in this space. These types of programs are best positioned to overcome the financial sustainability challenge and, with stronger evidence to support their effectiveness in the U.S., could merit revisiting as the field develops.</p></body>
</html>

            "text": "Render a set of tiddlers matching a filter to separate files of a specified ContentType (defaults to `text/html`) and extension (defaults to `.html`).\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers <filter> <template> <pathname> [<type>] [<extension>] [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers [!is[system]] $:/core/templates/static.tiddler.html ./static text/plain\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny files in the target directory are deleted unless the ''noclean'' flag is specified. The target directory is recursively created if it is missing.\n"
        },

The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n"

        "$:/language/Help/savetiddlers": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/savetiddlers",
            "description": "Saves a group of raw tiddlers to a directory",
            "text": "Saves a group of tiddlers in their raw text or binary format to the specified directory.\n\n```\n--savetiddlers <filter> <pathname> [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nThe output directory is cleared of existing files before saving the specified files. The deletion can be disabled by specifying the ''noclean'' flag.\n\nAny missing directories in the pathname are automatically created.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host> <pathprefix>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number to serve from (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''pathprefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/setfield": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/setfield",
            "description": "Prepares external tiddlers for use",
            "text": "//Note that this command is experimental and may change or be replaced before being finalised//\n\nSets the specified field of a group of tiddlers to the result of wikifying a template tiddler with the `currentTiddler` variable set to the tiddler.\n\n```\n--setfield <filter> <fieldname> <templatetitle> <rendertype>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''filter'' - filter identifying the tiddlers to be affected\n* ''fieldname'' - the field to modify (defaults to \"text\")\n* ''templatetitle'' - the tiddler to wikify into the specified field. If blank or missing then the specified field is deleted\n* ''rendertype'' - the text type to render (defaults to \"text/plain\"; \"text/html\" can be used to include HTML tags)\n"

Usage\n\nWhen the plugin is installed it automatically applies highlighting to all codeblocks defined with triple backticks or with the CodeBlockWidget.\n\nThe language can optionally be specified after the opening triple braces:\n\n<$codeblock code=\"\"\"```css\n * { margin: 0; padding: 0; } /* micro reset */\n\nhtml { font-size: 62.5%; }\nbody { font-size: 14px; font-size: 1.4rem; } /* =14px */\nh1   { font-size: 24px; font-size: 2.4rem; } /* =24px */\n```\"\"\"/>\n\nIf no language is specified highlight.js will attempt to automatically detect the language.\n\n! Built-in Language Brushes\n\nThe plugin includes support for the following languages (referred to as \"brushes\" by highlight.js):\n\n* apache\n* bash\n* coffeescript\n* cpp\n* cs\n* css\n* diff\n* http\n* ini\n* java\n* javascript\n* json\n* makefile\n* markdown\n* nginx\n* objectivec\n* perl\n* php\n* python\n* ruby\n* sql\n* xml\n\n"

        "$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/markdown/markdown.js": {
            "type": "application/javascript",
            "title": "$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/markdown/markdown.js",
            "module-type": "library",
            "text": "// Released under MIT license\n// Copyright (c) 2009-2010 Dominic Baggott\n// Copyright (c) 2009-2010 Ash Berlin\n// Copyright (c) 2011 Christoph Dorn <christoph@christophdorn.com> (http://www.christophdorn.com)\n\n/*jshint browser:true, devel:true */\n\n(function( expose ) {\n\n/**\n *  class Markdown\n *\n *  Markdown processing in Javascript done right. We have very particular views\n *  on what constitutes 'right' which include:\n *\n *  - produces well-formed HTML (this means that em and strong nesting is\n *    important)\n *\n *  - has an intermediate representation to allow processing of parsed data (We\n *    in fact have two, both as [JsonML]: a markdown tree and an HTML tree).\n *\n *  - is easily extensible to add new dialects without having to rewrite the\n *    entire parsing mechanics\n *\n *  - has a good test suite\n *\n *  This implementation fulfills all of these (except that the test suite could\n *  do with expanding to automatically run all the fixtures from other Markdown\n *  implementations.)\n *\n *  ##### Intermediate Representation\n *\n *  *TODO* Talk about this :) Its JsonML, but document the node names we use.\n *\n *  [JsonML]: http://jsonml.org/ \"JSON Markup Language\"\n **/\nvar Markdown = expose.Markdown = function(dialect) {\n  switch (typeof dialect) {\n    case \"undefined\":\n      this.dialect = Markdown.dialects.Gruber;\n      break;\n    case \"object\":\n      this.dialect = dialect;\n      break;\n    default:\n      if ( dialect in Markdown.dialects ) {\n        this.dialect = Markdown.dialects[dialect];\n      }\n      else {\n        throw new Error(\"Unknown Markdown dialect '\" + String(dialect) + \"'\");\n      }\n      break;\n  }\n  this.em_state = [];\n  this.strong_state = [];\n  this.debug_indent = \"\";\n};\n\n/**\n *  parse( markdown, [dialect] ) -> JsonML\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - dialect (String | Dialect): the dialect to use, defaults to gruber\n *\n *  Parse `markdown` and return a markdown document as a Markdown.JsonML tree.\n **/\nexpose.parse = function( source, dialect ) {\n  // dialect will default if undefined\n  var md = new Markdown( dialect );\n  return md.toTree( source );\n};\n\n/**\n *  toHTML( markdown, [dialect]  ) -> String\n *  toHTML( md_tree ) -> String\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - md_tree (Markdown.JsonML): parsed markdown tree\n *\n *  Take markdown (either as a string or as a JsonML tree) and run it through\n *  [[toHTMLTree]] then turn it into a well-formated HTML fragment.\n **/\nexpose.toHTML = function toHTML( source , dialect , options ) {\n  var input = expose.toHTMLTree( source , dialect , options );\n\n  return expose.renderJsonML( input );\n};\n\n/**\n *  toHTMLTree( markdown, [dialect] ) -> JsonML\n *  toHTMLTree( md_tree ) -> JsonML\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - dialect (String | Dialect): the dialect to use, defaults to gruber\n *  - md_tree (Markdown.JsonML): parsed markdown tree\n *\n *  Turn markdown into HTML, represented as a JsonML tree. If a string is given\n *  to this function, it is first parsed into a markdown tree by calling\n *  [[parse]].\n **/\nexpose.toHTMLTree = function toHTMLTree( input, dialect , options ) {\n  // convert string input to an MD tree\n  if ( typeof input ===\"string\" ) input = this.parse( input, dialect );\n\n  // Now convert the MD tree to an HTML tree\n\n  // remove references from the tree\n  var attrs = extract_attr( input ),\n      refs = {};\n\n  if ( attrs && attrs.references ) {\n    refs = attrs.references;\n  }\n\n  var html = convert_tree_to_html( input, refs , options );\n  merge_text_nodes( html );\n  return html;\n};\n\n// For Spidermonkey based engines\nfunction mk_block_toSource() {\n  return \"Markdown.mk_block( \" +\n          uneval(this.toString()) +\n          \", \" +\n          uneval(this.trailing) +\n          \", \" +\n          uneval(this.lineNumber) +\n          \" )\";\n}\n\n// node\nfunction mk_block_inspect() {\n  var util = require(\"util\");\n  return \"Markdown.mk_block( \" +\n          util.inspect(this.toString()) +\n          \", \" +\n          util.inspect(this.trailing) +\n          \", \" +\n          util.inspect(this.lineNumber) +\n          \" )\";\n\n}\n\nvar mk_block = Markdown.mk_block = function(block, trail, line) {\n  // Be helpful for default case in tests.\n  if ( arguments.length == 1 ) trail = \"\\n\\n\";\n\n  var s = new String(block);\n  s.trailing = trail;\n  // To make it clear its not just a string\n  s.inspect = mk_block_inspect;\n  s.toSource = mk_block_toSource;\n\n  if ( line != undefined )\n    s.lineNumber = line;\n\n  return s;\n};\n\nfunction count_lines( str ) {\n  var n = 0, i = -1;\n  while ( ( i = str.indexOf(\"\\n\", i + 1) ) !== -1 ) n++;\n  return n;\n}\n\n// Internal - split source into rough blocks\nMarkdown.prototype.split_blocks = function splitBlocks( input, startLine ) {\n  input = input.replace(/(\\r\\n|\\n|\\r)/g, \"\\n\");\n  // [\\s\\S] matches _anything_ (newline or space)\n  // [^] is equivalent but doesn't work in IEs.\n  var re = /([\\s\\S]+?)($|\\n#|\\n(?:\\s*\\n|$)+)/g,\n      blocks = [],\n      m;\n\n  var line_no = 1;\n\n  if ( ( m = /^(\\s*\\n)/.exec(input) ) != null ) {\n    // skip (but count) leading blank lines\n    line_no += count_lines( m[0] );\n    re.lastIndex = m[0].length;\n  }\n\n  while ( ( m = re.exec(input) ) !== null ) {\n    if (m[2] == \"\\n#\") {\n      m[2] = \"\\n\";\n      re.lastIndex--;\n    }\n    blocks.push( mk_block( m[1], m[2], line_no ) );\n    line_no += count_lines( m[0] );\n  }\n\n  return blocks;\n};\n\n/**\n *  Markdown#processBlock( block, next ) -> undefined | [ JsonML, ... ]\n *  - block (String): the block to process\n *  - next (Array): the following blocks\n *\n * Process `block` and return an array of JsonML nodes representing `block`.\n *\n * It does this by asking each block level function in the dialect to process\n * the block until one can. Succesful handling is indicated by returning an\n * array (with zero or more JsonML nodes), failure by a false value.\n *\n * Blocks handlers are responsible for calling [[Markdown#processInline]]\n * themselves as appropriate.\n *\n * If the blocks were split incorrectly or adjacent blocks need collapsing you\n * can adjust `next` in place using shift/splice etc.\n *\n * If any of this default behaviour is not right for the dialect, you can\n * define a `__call__` method on the dialect that will get invoked to handle\n * the block processing.\n */\nMarkdown.prototype.processBlock = function processBlock( block, next ) {\n  var cbs = this.dialect.block,\n      ord = cbs.__order__;\n\n  if ( \"__call__\" in cbs ) {\n    return cbs.__call__.call(this, block, next);\n  }\n\n  for ( var i = 0; i < ord.length; i++ ) {\n    //D:this.debug( \"Testing\", ord[i] );\n    var res = cbs[ ord[i] ].call( this, block, next );\n    if ( res ) {\n      //D:this.debug(\"  matched\");\n      if ( !isArray(res) || ( res.length > 0 && !( isArray(res[0]) ) ) )\n        this.debug(ord[i], \"didn't return a proper array\");\n      //D:this.debug( \"\" );\n      return res;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Uhoh! no match! Should we throw an error?\n  return [];\n};\n\nMarkdown.prototype.processInline = function processInline( block ) {\n  return this.dialect.inline.__call__.call( this, String( block ) );\n};\n\n/**\n *  Markdown#toTree( source ) -> JsonML\n *  - source (String): markdown source to parse\n *\n *  Parse `source` into a JsonML tree representing the markdown document.\n **/\n// custom_tree means set this.tree to `custom_tree` and restore old value on return\nMarkdown.prototype.toTree = function toTree( source, custom_root ) {\n  var blocks = source instanceof Array ? source : this.split_blocks( source );\n\n  // Make tree a member variable so its easier to mess with in extensions\n  var old_tree = this.tree;\n  try {\n    this.tree = custom_root || this.tree || [ \"markdown\" ];\n\n    blocks:\n    while ( blocks.length ) {\n      var b = this.processBlock( blocks.shift(), blocks );\n\n      // Reference blocks and the like won't return any content\n      if ( !b.length ) continue blocks;\n\n      this.tree.push.apply( this.tree, b );\n    }\n    return this.tree;\n  }\n  finally {\n    if ( custom_root ) {\n      this.tree = old_tree;\n    }\n  }\n};\n\n// Noop by default\nMarkdown.prototype.debug = function () {\n  var args = Array.prototype.slice.call( arguments);\n  args.unshift(this.debug_indent);\n  if ( typeof print !== \"undefined\" )\n      print.apply( print, args );\n  if ( typeof console !== \"undefined\" && typeof console.log !== \"undefined\" )\n      console.log.apply( null, args );\n}\n\nMarkdown.prototype.loop_re_over_block = function( re, block, cb ) {\n  // Dont use /g regexps with this\n  var m,\n      b = block.valueOf();\n\n  while ( b.length && (m = re.exec(b) ) != null ) {\n    b = b.substr( m[0].length );\n    cb.call(this, m);\n  }\n  return b;\n};\n\n/**\n * Markdown.dialects\n *\n * Namespace of built-in dialects.\n **/\nMarkdown.dialects = {};\n\n/**\n * Markdown.dialects.Gruber\n *\n * The default dialect that follows the rules set out by John Gruber's\n * markdown.pl as closely as possible. Well actually we follow the behaviour of\n * that script which in some places is not exactly what the syntax web page\n * says.\n **/\nMarkdown.dialects.Gruber = {\n  block: {\n    atxHeader: function atxHeader( block, next ) {\n      var m = block.match( /^(#{1,6})\\s*(.*?)\\s*#*\\s*(?:\\n|$)/ );\n\n      if ( !m ) return undefined;\n\n      var header = [ \"header\", { level: m[ 1 ].length } ];\n      Array.prototype.push.apply(header, this.processInline(m[ 2 ]));\n\n      if ( m[0].length < block.length )\n        next.unshift( mk_block( block.substr( m[0].length ), block.trailing, block.lineNumber + 2 ) );\n\n      return [ header ];\n    },\n\n    setextHeader: function setextHeader( block, next ) {\n      var m = block.match( /^(.*)\\n([-=])\\2\\2+(?:\\n|$)/ );\n\n      if ( !m ) return undefined;\n\n      var level = ( m[ 2 ] === \"=\" ) ? 1 : 2;\n      var header = [ \"header\", { level : level }, m[ 1 ] ];\n\n      if ( m[0].length < block.length )\n        next.unshift( mk_block( block.substr( m[0].length ), block.trailing, block.lineNumber + 2 ) );\n\n      return [ header ];\n    },\n\n    code: function code( block, next ) {\n      // |    Foo\n      // |bar\n      // should be a code block followed by a paragraph.             "text": "! Markdown Dialects\n\nBy default the markdown parser recognises the original dialect of Markdown [[as described by John Gruber|http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/]]. An extended dialect called \"Maruku\" is also included that provides table support and other advanced features. The syntax extensions are modelled on those of [[PHP Markdown Extra|https://michelf.ca/projects/php-markdown/extra/]].\n\nThe configuration tiddler [[$:/config/markdown/dialect]] determines which dialect is used:\n\n|!Dialect |!Description |\n|Gruber |Standard Markdown |\n|Maruku |Extended Maruku Markdown |\n\n\n! Creating ~WikiLinks\n\nCreate wiki links with the usual Markdown link syntax targeting `#` and the target tiddler title:\n\n```\n[link text](#TiddlerTitle)\n```\n\n! Images\n\nMarkdown image syntax can be used to reference images by tiddler title or an external URI. For example:\n\n```\n![alt text](/path/to/img.jpg \"Title\")\n\n![alt text](Motovun Jack.jpg \"Title\")\n```\n"
        },

            "text": "! The `--fillet` Command\n\nThis plugin adds the `--fillet` command (like all commands, it is only available when running under Node.js):\n\n```\ntiddlywiki wiki --fillet \"Raw Pipeline\" --build index\n```\n\nThe command fillets the specified HTML tiddler into individual tiddlers as described below.\n\n! Filleting Process\n\n* Heading 1: \"Introduction\"\n*> Outputs the body text in a tiddler titled \"Introduction\"\n* Heading 1: \"Organizations\"\n** Heading 2: {name of domain}\n**> Outputs a tiddler titled with the name of the domain, and the tag \"domain\"\n*** Heading 3: {name of sub-domain}\n***> Outputs a tiddler titled with the name of the sub-domain, and the tag \"sub-domain\"\n**** Heading 4: {name of organization}\n****> Outputs a tiddler titled with the name of the organization, the field \"issue-area\" set to the issue area below, the field \"domain\" set to the domain, and the field \"sub-domain\" set to the sub-domain, and the tag \"organization\"\n***** Heading 5: \"Issue Area\"\n*****> Body text is used for the \"issue-area\" field of the organization tiddler\n***** Heading 5: \"Logo\"\n*****> Outputs the image in a tiddler titled with the name of the organization with \"(Logo)\" appended, and tagged with the name of the organization, and the field \"organization-info\" set to \"logo\"\n***** Heading 5: \"Description\"\n*****> Outputs the body text in a tiddler titled with the name of the organization with \"(Description)\" appended, and tagged with the name of the organization, and the field \"organization-info\" set to \"description\"\n***** Heading 5: \"Summary Assessment\"\n*****> Outputs the body text in a tiddler titled with the name of the organization with \"(Summary Assessment)\" appended, and tagged with the name of the organization, and the field \"organization-info\" set to \"summary-assessment\"\n***** Heading 5: \"Current View\"\n*****> Outputs the body text in a tiddler titled with the name of the organization with \"(Current View)\" appended, and tagged with the name of the organization, and the field \"organization-info\" set to \"current-view\"\n\n* Heading 1: \"Issue Areas\"\n** Heading 2: {name of issue area}\n**> Outputs the body text in tiddlers titled with the name of the issue area, and the tag \"issue-area\"\n"

        },
        "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/settings/backgroundimageattachment": {
            "title": "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/settings/backgroundimageattachment",
            "text": "fixed"
        },
        "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/settings/backgroundimagesize": {
            "title": "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/settings/backgroundimagesize",
            "text": "auto"
        },
        "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/sticky": {
            "title": "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/sticky",
            "text": "<$reveal state=\"$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/options/stickytitles\" type=\"match\" text=\"yes\">\n``\n.tc-tiddler-title {\n\tposition: -webkit-sticky;\n\tposition: -moz-sticky;\n\tposition: -o-sticky;\n\tposition: -ms-sticky;\n\tposition: sticky;\n\ttop: 0px;\n\tbackground: ``<<colour tiddler-background>>``;\n\tz-index: 500;\n}\n``\n</$reveal>\n"
        }
    }
}

This is a wiki, written in [[TiddlyWiki|http://tiddlywiki.com]]. It has a custom user interface designed to make the information easy to explore.

<<<
<<switch-theme-tw "TiddlyWiki Mode">> to return to the standard ~TiddlyWiki user interface.

<<switch-theme-bmp "Essay Mode">> to return to the custom Essay interface.
<<<

A wiki is an interactive text. Wikipedia is a wiki; its "text" consists of all the articles available under its umbrella.

[[TiddlyWiki|http://tiddlywiki.com]] is "an open-source single page application wiki in the form of a single HTML file that includes CSS, JavaScript, and the content. It is designed to be easy to customize and re-shape depending on application. It facilitates re-use of content by dividing it into small pieces called Tiddlers" ([[Wikipedia|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TiddlyWiki]]).

TiddlyWikis can be shared as documents in the same way as other document files, like Word files or PDFs.

\define organization-count(filter)
<div class="tc-drilldown-tabs-item-count">
<$list filter="$filter$ +[limit[1]]" emptyMessage="""
no organizations
""">
<$count filter="$filter$"/>
<$list filter="$filter$ +[butfirst[]limit[1]]" emptyMessage="""
organization
""">
organizations
</$list>
</$list>
</div>
\end

\define foldable-description(title)
<div class="tc-drilldown-description">
<$reveal type="nomatch" state="$:/state/foldable-description/$title$" text="show">
<$set name="tv-hide-more" value="yes">
<$set name="tv-hide-more-controls" value="""
<p>
<$button class="tc-drilldown-description-button tc-btn-invisible">
<$action-setfield $tiddler="$:/state/foldable-description/$title$" $value="show"/>
more...
</$button>
</p>
""">
<$transclude tiddler={{$title$}}/>
</$set>
</$set>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" state="$:/state/foldable-description/$title$" text="show">
<$set name="tv-hide-more-controls" value="""
<p>
<$button class="tc-drilldown-description-button tc-btn-invisible">
<$action-deletetiddler $tiddler="$:/state/foldable-description/$title$"/>
less...
</$button>
</p>
""">
<$transclude tiddler={{$title$}}/>
</$set>
</$reveal>
</div>
\end

\define domain-button(classes,clickStateValue)
<$button tag="div" class="tc-drilldown-domain tc-drilldown-tabs-item $classes$">
<$action-setfield $tiddler="$:/state/_browse/domain" $value="""$clickStateValue$"""/>
<$action-deletetiddler $tiddler="$:/state/_browse/sub-domain"/>
<$action-deletetiddler $tiddler="$:/state/_browse/organization"/>
<div class="tc-drilldown-tabs-item-heading">
<$view tiddler=<<domain>> field="title"/>
<<organization-count "[role[organization]tag<domain>]">>
</div>
<$reveal type="match" state="$:/state/_browse/domain" text="" tag="div">
<$set name="tv-hide-more" value="yes">
<$transclude tiddler=<<domain>> mode="block"/>
</$set>
</$reveal>
</$button>
\end

\define sub-domain-button(classes,clickStateValue)

</div>

<$transclude tiddler=<<sub-domain>> mode="block"/>
</$set>
</$reveal>
</$button>
\end

! Filleting Process

This content of this wiki is extracted from a specially formatted Word document. The first step is to convert it into HTML format (see it [[here|$:/_RawPipeline]]), and then the filleting plugin is used to slice the sections into individual tiddlers that are woven together through their metadata.

{{$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/text-fillet/docs}}







This is a demo of an navigable essay


















<$list filter="[role[domain]]">




































This great trick was shown to the tiddlywiki google group by [[Alberto Molina|https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/tiddlywiki/OCntQ79DuwM]]. I enhanced it a bit.

|!Search tag: | <$edit-text tiddler="$:/temp/RenameTags/search" tag="input" type="text"/> |
|!Replace by: | <$edit-text tiddler="$:/temp/RenameTags/replace" tag="input" type="text"/> |

---
<$reveal type="nomatch" text="" state="$:/temp/RenameTags/replace">

!First step
!!//Apply the tag <$tiddler tiddler={{$:/temp/RenameTags/replace}}><$transclude tiddler="$:/core/ui/TagTemplate"/></$tiddler> to the following tiddlers//
<$list filter="[!has[draft.of]tag{$:/temp/RenameTags/search}!tag{$:/temp/RenameTags/replace}sort[created]]">
<$checkbox tag={{$:/temp/RenameTags/replace}}> <$link to={{!!title}}><$view field="title"/></$link></$checkbox><br/>
</$list>
</$reveal>

<$reveal type="nomatch" text="" state="$:/temp/RenameTags/search">

!Second step
!!//Remove the tag <$tiddler tiddler={{$:/temp/RenameTags/search}}><$transclude tiddler="$:/core/ui/TagTemplate"/></$tiddler> from the following tiddlers//
<$list filter="[!has[draft.of]tag{$:/temp/RenameTags/search}tag{$:/temp/RenameTags/replace}sort[created]]">
<$checkbox tag={{$:/temp/RenameTags/search}}> ~~<$link to={{!!title}}><$view field="title"/></$link>~~</$checkbox><br/>
</$list>
</$reveal>
